A vibrant, hyper-stylized tableau where two male models, embodying Pierre et Gilles' signature Baroque-meets-kitsch aesthetic, stand against a backdrop of hand-painted celestial clouds gilded with gold leaf. One model wears a ruffled Rococo jacket in candy-floss pink, embroidered with tiny mirrored sequins that catch the light like shattered stained glass, while the other dives into a sailor's uniform reimagined in liquid silver lamé, his collar adorned with seashell cameos.
Their faces are powdered porcelain-white, lips glossed cherry-red, eyes lined with exaggerated cobalt streaks that melt into tiny rhinestone tears. Between them floats an oversized translucent bubble containing a miniature Eiffel Tower wrapped in neon ivy, while artificial roses
-dipped in iridescent resin- sprout from their epaulettes like surreal shoulder gardens. The scene is drenched in saturated jewel tones, shadows painted out entirely, every element glowing as if lit from within by Technicolor votives.

images.alt: Here's a headless doubleneck bass/guitar contraption that avant-garde guitarist Elliott Sharp built. The bass neck came from a Fender Coronado bass, and the guitar neck came from a Schecter Strat. The bass has a P pickup and a J pickup, and the guitar has a Tele bridge pickup and a Strat neck pickup. Each neck has its own 3-way switch, but no volume or tone knobs. The volume is controlled by separate volume pedals for each neck. There's also an IVL Pitchrider 7000 guitar-to-MIDI converter that E# used to trigger samples. (You can see the pickup for that jammed right next to the guitar bridge.) The tuners are all in a row at the end of the body.
